ite Castle quickly established itself as a cornerstone of the fast food industry. Its founder, Billy Ingram, shrewdly marketed his hamburgers in large quantities at five cents a piece, telling his customers to "Buy'em by the Sack." The years following World War II saw the rise of great franchised chains such as McDonald's, which challenged and ultimately overshadowed the company that Billy Ingram founded. Yet White Castle stands as a charismatic pioneer in one of America's most formidable industries, a company that drastically changed American eating patterns, and hence, American life. It could be argued that what Henry Ford did for the car and transportation, Billy Ingram did for the hamburger and eating.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aRestaurateurszUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Interest.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081473566440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814744529.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814744529423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814744529/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK